---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { SiteChromeBoot } from "../components/SiteChromeBoot";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Tonet"
  description="What Tonet is: a lightweight Servo-based browser, open development, and how it relates to projects like Blitz."
  page="about"
>
  <main class="legal-page">
    <h1>About Tonet</h1>
    <p class="legal-updated"><strong>Last updated:</strong> May 2, 2026</p>
    <p class="legal-lang-note" role="note">
      <strong>Language:</strong> This page is available in <strong>English only</strong>. It is not part of the site’s translated interface; the
      language selector in the footer only affects navigation labels on other pages.
    </p>

    <p>
      Tonet is an <strong>open source desktop browser</strong> built around the <strong>Servo</strong> rendering engine and a deliberately
      minimal shell. The goal is to offer a fast, understandable surface for reading and search—with explicit policies (such as resource limits)
      instead of chasing full compatibility with the entire modern web stack on day one.
    </p>

    <h2>Vision</h2>
    <p>
      Mainstream browsers optimize for maximal web compatibility, which often means large runtimes, opaque update channels, and broad telemetry
      surfaces. Tonet takes the opposite bet: <strong>clarity over coverage</strong> for early releases—documented behavior, operator-controlled
      update manifests, and a stack you can reason about when deploying inside a team or organization.
    </p>

    <h2>Servo engine</h2>
    <p>
      Web content is rendered with <strong>Servo</strong>, not Chromium, WebKit, or CEF. Servo is an independent engine with strong standards
      credentials; Tonet adds packaging, policy, and UX choices on top. See the project repository for integration status and platform notes.
    </p>

    <h2>Open development</h2>
    <p>
      Source code, issue tracking, and release engineering live in public on <a
        href="https://github.com/usetonet/tonet-browser"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>. Installers and documentation describe how updates are verified and how operators can host their own
      CDN layouts.
    </p>

    <h2>Related work: Blitz</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Blitz</strong> is a separate open source effort: a modular web engine written in Rust, aimed at embeddability, alternative HTML use
      cases (e.g. rendering subsets of the web stack), and experimentation—not at replacing every mainstream browser overnight. It shares the
      broader ecosystem goal of giving developers composable engine pieces rather than only monolithic forks.
    </p>
    <p>
      Tonet is <strong>not</strong> Blitz; Tonet ships as a browser product on Servo. If you want to compare philosophies—modular runtime vs.
      Tonet’s Servo-first shell—see the Blitz project materials on
      <a href="https://github.com/DioxusLabs/blitz" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub (DioxusLabs/blitz)</a> and upstream docs.
    </p>

    <h2>Status</h2>
    <p>
      Tonet is under active development. Capability matrices, roadmap phases, and quality gates are published in the repo and on
      <a href="/roadmap.html">Roadmap</a>. Nothing on this page is a guarantee of future features or timelines.
    </p>
  </main>
  <SiteChromeBoot client:load />
</BaseLayout>
